Here's an expanded list covering the broader Kubernetes ecosystem tooling and commands beyond core kubectl/kubeadm.
Helm (package manager)

helm install — install a chart
helm upgrade — upgrade a release
helm uninstall — remove a release
helm rollback — roll back to a previous revision
helm list / helm ls — list releases
helm status — release status
helm repo add/update/list/remove — manage chart repos
helm search repo/hub — search charts
helm pull — download a chart
helm template — render templates locally
helm lint — validate a chart
helm create — scaffold a new chart
helm package — package a chart
helm history — release revision history
helm get values/manifest/notes — inspect a release
helm dependency update/build — manage chart dependencies
helm show values/chart/readme — inspect a chart

Kustomize

kustomize build — render manifests
kustomize create — create a kustomization.yaml
kustomize edit — modify kustomization (add resource, set image, etc.)
kubectl apply -k / kubectl kustomize — built-in equivalents

minikube (local cluster)

minikube start/stop/delete
minikube status
minikube dashboard
minikube service — expose a service
minikube addons enable/disable/list
minikube tunnel — route LoadBalancer services
minikube ssh
minikube image load

kind (Kubernetes in Docker)

kind create cluster
kind delete cluster
kind get clusters/nodes
kind load docker-image — load image into cluster
kind export logs

k3s / k3d (lightweight)

k3s server / k3s agent
k3s kubectl — bundled kubectl
k3d cluster create/delete/list
k3d node create
k3d image import

crictl (CRI debugging)

crictl ps — list containers
crictl pods — list pods
crictl images — list images
crictl logs — container logs
crictl exec — exec into container
crictl inspect — inspect container/pod
crictl pull — pull image

etcdctl (etcd management)

etcdctl snapshot save/restore — backup/restore
etcdctl member list/add/remove
etcdctl get/put/del
etcdctl endpoint health/status

TUI / Dashboard tools (third-party)

k9s — terminal UI for clusters
kubectx — switch contexts quickly
kubens — switch namespaces quickly
stern — multi-pod log tailing
kubectl-tree (krew) — show resource ownership tree
lens — GUI dashboard
Kubernetes Dashboard — official web UI

GitOps / CD tools

argocd app create/sync/get/list — Argo CD CLI
flux bootstrap/get/reconcile/install — FluxCD CLI

Security / Policy

kubeseal — Sealed Secrets
kube-bench — CIS benchmark checks
kube-hunter — penetration testing
trivy — image/cluster vulnerability scanning
falco — runtime security
opa / conftest — policy evaluation (OPA/Gatekeeper)
kyverno CLI — policy testing

Networking / Service Mesh

istioctl install/analyze/proxy-status/dashboard — Istio
linkerd install/check/viz — Linkerd
cilium install/status/connectivity test — Cilium
calicoctl — Calico management

Observability

kubectl top (Metrics Server)
promtool — Prometheus rule/config checking
kubectl-trace — eBPF tracing
Prometheus / Grafana / Loki (deployed in-cluster, not CLIs per se)

Scaling / Cost

kubectl-cost (krew) — cost analysis
KEDA — event-driven autoscaling (CRDs, no main CLI)
Karpenter — node autoscaling (config-driven)

Misc Utilities

kubeconform / kubeval — manifest validation
kompose convert — Docker Compose → K8s manifests
velero backup/restore/schedule — cluster backup/DR
helmfile — declarative Helm release management
sops — secrets encryption
krew — kubectl plugin manager (kubectl krew install/list/search)

This rounds out the practical ecosystem: package management, local clusters, CRI/etcd internals, GitOps, security, service mesh, observability, and backup/DR tooling. Most production setups use some mix of these on top of core kubectl.